article.description: When Nick Welch wasn't popping a 3-pointer, he was using his quickness to drive around BYU's Rafael Araujo for a layup.
article.headline: Welch dunks and shoots way to 20 points
article.linkText: Air Force tops BYU for record 11th straight win
article.story: AIR FORCE ACADEMY, Colo. (AP) -- When Nick Welch wasn't popping a 3-pointer, he was using his quickness to drive around BYU's Rafael Araujo for a layup. Welch scored a career-high 20 points on 9-of-10 shooting Saturday to lead Air Force to a 74-52 romp over BYU. A.J. Kuhle added 14 points, Tim Keller 12 and Antoine Hood 11 as Air Force (13-2, 3-0 Mountain West) extended its winning streak to 11 games, a school record. BYU (12-5, 2-2) was led by Mark Bigelow's 19 points. Araujo, the conference's leading scorer and rebounder, was held to 12 points and six rebounds. "All week long everybody was asking how we were going to stop Araujo," Air Force coach Joe Scott said. "I didn't have one guy ask me how Araujo was going to stop Welch. "With Nick Welch as our center, we have a guy who can take advantage of some matchups in our favor, and that was a big key for us. Nick played terrific." The Falcons, off to the best start in school history, shot 73 percent compared to BYU's 43 percent. Air Force -- which entered the game with the nation's best scoring defense, limiting opponents to 46.6 points per game -- held the Cougars 24 points below their season average. It was Air Force's largest winning margin ever over BYU, and it represented the Cougars' biggest loss ever in Mountain West regular-season play. "This was a huge win," Scott said. "To perform like this, I think we let everybody in America know that right now this is one of the best teams in America, bar none. A win like this sort of cements that. "We beat one of the favorites to win the league, and we've got the other one (Utah) coming into our building on Monday night." Before a record Clune Arena crowd of 6,359, the Falcons never trailed, jumping out to a quick lead, expanding it to 42-19 at halftime and building as much as a 27-point lead in the second half. Welch said the Falcons, who defeated Colorado State and New Mexico last week, "made a statement tonight. At Colorado State, (CSU center) Matt Nelson didn't play, and people said their best player wasn't there. Then people said New Mexico maybe wasn't that good of a team. But to play like that against BYU makes a statement." BYU coach Steve Cleveland had to agree. "We got beat in every aspect of the game," Cleveland said. "They took it to us in the beginning, and we never really regrouped. Welch just absolutely killed us. Air Force was the aggressor tonight, and we were a little bit back on our heels." Bigelow said the difference in this year's Air Force team is that "everybody can shoot. Last year there were a couple of guys you didn't have to guard. This year you have to guard everyone." Kuhle had 12 points and Welch 11 in the first half as Air Force, using a 19-3 run, took a 23-point halftime lead. The Falcons outshot BYU 73 percent to 29 percent in the half. Air Force hit its first six shots, including a pair of 3-pointers, while BYU was committing five turnovers as the Falcons forged a 14-4 lead. Kuhle, Tim Keller and Marcus Jenkins all hit 3-pointers as Air Force stretched its lead to 23-10 midway through the half. BYU scored the next six points, capped by Luiz Lemes' baseline jumper, to cut the deficit to 23-16 with 8:12 left, but Air Force responded with its 19-3 surge to close out the half. Welch started it with a pair of driving layups. BYU's Mark Bigelow had a short jumper off the glass, but Air Force scored the next eight points, including Kuhle's layup on a pass from Hood. Welch had another driving layup past Araujo for a 33-18 lead. Hood beat the shot clock with a 3-pointer and followed with a steal and a slam dunk at the other end for a 40-19 lead. Bigelow scored the first five points of the second half to cut the deficit to 18, but Air Force countered with a 13-4 flurry, including two layups by Welch, for a 55-28 lead. BYU got no closer than 20 points after that.
